    {
      "id": "step-pronunciation",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Pronunciation tips",
      "body": "## A few traps\n\n- **Six** and **dix** end in /s/ when said alone (\"sees\", \"deese\") but the /s/ disappears before a consonant (\"si livres\" — six books). Bend the rule for now; native speakers will understand both ways.\n- **Neuf** ends in /f/ except in two fixed expressions where it becomes /v/: **neuf ans** (nine years), **neuf heures** (nine o'clock).\n- **Huit** keeps its silent **h**: there's no aspirated H sound in French at all."
    },
